A D J U D I C A T I O N
BACKGROUND:
This proceeding arises out of a citation that was issued on April 10, 2002, by the Bureau of Liquor Control Enforcement of the Pennsylvania State Police (hereinafter Bureau) against Boden, Inc., t/a Clancys Pub, License Number R-AP-SS-EHF-1066 (hereinafter Licensee).
The citation charges Licensee with violation of Section 471 of the Liquor Code [47 P.S. Â§4-471] and Section 5513 of the Crimes Code [18 Pa.
C.S. Â§5513], in that on January 26, February 9 and 13, 2002, Licensee, by its servants, agents or employes, possessed or operated gambling devices or paraphernalia or permitted gambling or lotteries, poolselling and/or bookmaking on the licensed premises.
The investigation which gave rise to the citation began on November 12, 2001 and was completed on March 6, 2002; and notice of the violation was sent to Licensee by Certified Mail on March 26, 2002.
The notice of violation was received by Licensee on March 27, 2002.
An consolidated hearing with Citation No. 02-0805 was held on August 27, 2002 in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
Upon review of the transcript of this hearing, we make the following Findings of Fact and reach the following Conclusions of Law:
FINDINGS OF FACT: 1.
Licensee is a corporation located in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania and holds Restaurant Liquor License Number R-AP-SS-EHF-1066.
(N.T. 4) 2.
On Saturday, January 26, 2002 at 5:50 p.m., an enforcement officer entered the licensed premises and observed a bartender, Greg, rendering service of alcoholic beverages to 19 patrons.
3.
The officer observed three video poker machines and two video slot machines set up inside and operational.
(N.T. 7) 4.
At 6:18 p.m., the officer observed two patrons playing one of the video slot machines.
5.
The officer observed Licensees bartender make a notation on a piece of paper to the right of the cash register, looked at the video slot machine which had 400 credits on the display screen, removed an unknown amount of U.S. currency from the cash register and placed it on the bar in front of the patron who was playing the machine.
(N.T. 8) 6.
This patron moved from the machine to the bar and picked the money up.
(N.T. 8) 7.
The bartender then went directly to the video slot machine with a coin in his hand, reached around the rear of it and the credits were removed from the display screen.
(N.T. 8) 8.
A short time later, the two patrons returned to the same video slot machine, placed a $5.00 bill into it, were awarded 100 credits, and continued to play.
(N.T. 8) 9.
At 8:55 p.m., the officer departed the licensed premises.
(N.T. 8) 10.
On Saturday, February 9, 2002 at 9:30 p.m., the officer returned to the licensed premises and observed the same bartenders, Greg, along with Corporate President Duane Boden, rendering service of alcoholic beverages to approximately 50 patrons.
(N.T. 8-9) 11.
The officer observed the same two video poker machines and two video slot machines set up inside and operational.
(N.T. 9) 12.
At approximately 10:50 p.m., the officer observed a male patron play one of the Cherry Master video slot machines, accrue a score of 1000 points and inform the bartender, Greg, who looked at the machine, made a notation on a piece of paper and removed an undetermined amount of currency from the cash register which he paid to the patron.
(N.T. 9) 13.
The 1000 points were cleared from the video slot machine in an unknown manner counting down from 1000 to zero.
(N.T. 9) 14.
At 10:55 p.m., the officer departed the licensed premises.
(N.T. 9) 15.
On Wednesday, February 13, 2002 at 1:15 p.m., enforcement officers, armed with a search warrant, conducted an open inspection of the licensed premises and seized the three video poker machines and two video slot machines.
(N.T. 9-10) 16.
The officers inspected the five machines, placed U.S. currency into each, and found that credits could be knocked off via a set of four toggle switches behind the bar for four machines, and the fifth machine by placing metal to bolt heads located on the rear of the machine.
(N.T. 10-11, 13) 17.
Licensees corporate president, Duane Boden, was present during the open inspection and completed a gambling questionnaire in which he admitted the 50/50 split of the money with the machine vendor and the points needed for a gambling payoff.
(N.T. 12-13 Exhibit C-6) 18.
On March 6, 2002, an enforcement officer examined the five seized video gambling machines and found that each accepted U.S. currency, required no skill to play, had a knock-off device to clear credits, and had video or manual meter accounting to keep track of the coins in and games knocked off.
(N.T. 15-17)
CONCLUSIONS OF LAW:
Sustained as charged.
DISCUSSION:
A consolidated hearing with Citation No. 02-0805 was held at which the enforcement officer testified in detail as to observing Licensees bartender, Greg, make gambling payoffs to patrons on January 26, February 9 and 13, 2002, and seizing five video gambling machines on February 13, 2002.
The machines were examined on March 6, 2002 and found to be gambling devices per se.
Licensees corporate president, Duane T. Boden, appeared without counsel and did not dispute the officers testimony.
He thought he had waived this citation.
(N.T. 33) find the testimony of the officer to be credible and that the Bureau has met its burden of proof in this case.
As such, the citation is sustained as charged.
PRIOR RECORD:
Licensee has been licensed since May 1, 1996, and has had no prior violations.
PENALTY:
Section 471 of the Liquor Code [47 P.S. Â§4-471] prescribes a penalty of license suspension or revocation or a fine of not less than $50.00 or more than $1,000.00 or both for violations of the type found in this case.
Counsel for the Bureau recommended a $600.00 fine for a waiver of this case.
After due consideration of the circumstances giving rise to the citation, a $600.00 fine will be imposed.
ORDER:
THEREFORE, it is hereby ordered that Licensee, Boden, Inc., t/a Clancys Pub, pay a fine of $600.00 within 20 days of the mailing date of this Order.
In the event the aforementioned fine is not paid within 20 days from the mailing date of this Order, Licensees license shall be suspended or revoked.
The fine must be paid by Treasurers Check, Cashiers Check, Certified Check or Money Order.
Personal checks, which include business-use personal checks, are not acceptable.
Please make guaranteed check payable to the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania and mail to:
PLCB - Office of Administrative Law Judge Brandywine Plaza 2221 Paxton Church Road Harrisburg, PA 17110-9661
JURISDICTION IS RETAINED UNTIL CASE IS CLOSED.
Dated this _8th_ day of _October_, 2002.
